      "id": 354496,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Aromatic compounds such as benzene react with alkyl chlorides in the presence of AlCl<sub>3</sub> catalyst to yield alkylbenzenes. This reaction occurs through a carbocation intermediate, formed by reaction of the alkyl chloride with AlCl<sub>3</sub> (R−Cl + AlCl<sub>3</sub> ⟶ R<sup>+</sup> + AlCl<sub>4</sub><sup>−</sup>). How can you explain the observation that reaction of benzene with 1-chloropropane yields isopropylbenzene as the major product?</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaE1TIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--5d41292f92d43f2c1acece29c61ded0f397254f7/OChem_07_EC_036.jpg\" alt=\"Benzene reacts with propyl chloride in the presence of aluminum trichloride to form a benzene ring, in which C1 is bonded to an isopropyl group.\">",
